You can add authorization to your Nginx Docker container by using Nginx's built-in basic authentication feature. Here's a step-by-step guide:

1. Create an Nginx password file to store your credentials:
```bash
sudo apt-get install apache2-utils
sudo htpasswd -c /etc/nginx/.htpasswd username
```
Replace `username` with the username you want to use for authentication.

2. Modify your Nginx configuration to enable basic authentication:
```bash
server {
    listen 1935;
    server_name localhost;

    location / {
        auth_basic "Restricted Content";
        auth_basic_user_file /etc/nginx/.htpasswd;

        proxy_pass http://localhost:8080;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
    }
}
```
3. Restart your Nginx Docker container to apply the changes:
```
docker restart nginx
```
Now, when accessing the RTMP endpoint, users will be prompted to enter a username and password. The credentials will be checked against the `/etc/nginx/.htpasswd` file.

