To send the latitude and longitude values every 2 seconds over UDP using TypeScript, you can use the `setInterval` function to repeatedly call a function that sends the data. Here's an example code snippet:
```typescript
import * as dgram from 'dgram';

const client = dgram.createSocket('udp4');

const PORT = 1234;
const HOST = '127.0.0.1';

function sendLatLong() {
  const latitude = 37.7749;
  const longitude = -122.4194;

  const latHex = latitude.toString(16).padStart(8, '0');
  const longHex = longitude.toString(16).padStart(8, '0');
  const hexString = latHex + longHex;

  const data = Buffer.from(hexString, 'hex');

  client.send(data, 0, data.length, PORT, HOST, (err) => {
    if (err) {
      console.error(err);
    } else {
      console.log(`Sent data to ${HOST}:${PORT}`);
    }
  });
}

// Send the data every 2 seconds
setInterval(sendLatLong, 2000);
```
In this example, we define a function `sendLatLong` that encodes the latitude and longitude values as a hex string, converts the hex string to a buffer, and sends the resulting data packet over UDP using `client.send` method. We then use `setInterval` function to call the `sendLatLong` function every 2 seconds.

Note that in this example, we are sending the data to a local host on port 1234. You will need to replace the `HOST` and `PORT` values with the appropriate values for your use case. Also, ensure that the server is running and listening on the specified port to receive the data.

