Certainly! Here is the lookup function in pseudo-code, which should give you a high-level understanding of the code without getting into the specific details of any particular assembly language:
```
float lookup(int inputValue) {
  static const int tableSize = 10;
  static float look[tableSize][2] = {{0, 0}, {25, 0.04}, {50, 0.13}, {75, 0.29}, {100, 0.5}, 
                                    {125, 0.71}, {150, 0.87}, {175, 0.96}, {200, 0.99}, {255, 1}};

  float outputValue = 0;
  for (int i = 0; i < tableSize - 1; i++) {
    if (inputValue is within the range of segment i) {
      // Interpolate the output value using the values of the surrounding segments
      float slope = (look[i+1][1] - look[i][1]) / (look[i+1][0] - look[i][0]);
      outputValue = look[i][1] + slope * (inputValue - look[i][0]);
      break;
    }
  }

  return outputValue;
}
```
This pseudo-code should give you a general idea of how the lookup function works. It first defines a lookup table with 10 segments, and then it iterates through the segments to find the appropriate one for the given input value. It then interpolates the output value using the values of the surrounding segments, and returns the result.

